!! Why tw-upload exists

MCP clients like Claude CLI communicate with the MCP server via ''stdio'' (standard input/output). This transport is text-based and not designed for large binary data. Sending a 5MB image as base64 through stdio would consume ~7MB of tokens and likely hit buffer limits.

The `tw-upload` helper solves this by using the MCP server's ''named pipe'' transport instead. It reads the file locally, base64-encodes it, and sends it directly to the server over the pipe — bypassing the AI client entirely. The AI never sees the binary data.

!! How it works

# The MCP server starts a named pipe alongside stdio and writes connection details to `.tw-mcp/connect`
# `tw-upload` reads the connect file to find the pipe path and auth token
# It connects to the pipe, authenticates, and calls the `upload_file` tool with the base64-encoded file
# The server saves the file to the wiki's `files/` directory and creates a tiddler with `_canonical_uri` pointing to it

!! Supported file types

|! Extension |! MIME type |
|`.png` |`image/png` |
|`.jpg` / `.jpeg` |`image/jpeg` |
|`.gif` |`image/gif` |
|`.pdf` |`application/pdf` |

Maximum file size: ''50 MB''

!! Usage

```
cd /your/wiki/dir
node tw-upload.js <file> [--wiki <path>] [--title <title>] [--tags <tags>] [--subfolder <dir>]
```

|! Option |! Description |
|`<file>` |File to upload (required) |
|`--wiki <path>` |Wiki directory to find `.tw-mcp/connect` (defaults to current dir) |
|`--title <title>` |Tiddler title (defaults to filename) |
|`--tags <tags>` |Space-separated tags (use `[[double brackets]]` for multi-word tags) |
|`--subfolder <dir>` |Subfolder within `files/` to save to |

!! Examples

```
node tw-upload.js photo.png
node tw-upload.js doc.pdf --title "My Document" --tags "docs reference"
node tw-upload.js icon.gif --subfolder images --tags "[[site images]]"
```

!! Requirements

* The MCP server must be running (`tiddlywiki . --mcp`)
* The `.tw-mcp/connect` file must exist (created automatically by the server)
* Node.js must be available

If the connect file is missing, `tw-upload` will show a clear error with instructions to start the server.

!! Security

* ''Pipe authentication'' — `tw-upload` reads the 256-bit auth token from `.tw-mcp/connect` and sends it with the initialize request. Unauthenticated connections are rejected.
* ''Terminal injection protection'' — server responses are sanitised to strip ANSI escape codes before printing to the terminal.
* ''Path restrictions'' — files are saved to the wiki's `files/` directory, which is within the server's allowed paths.